    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-item"><label>Timeline</label><span>8 weeks</span></div>
      <div class="stat-item"><label>Role</label><span>Solo Build</span></div>
      <div class="stat-item"><label>Tools</label><span>Arduino Uno, Fusion 360</span></div>
      <div class="stat-item"><label>Result</label><span>&lt;2% deviation rate</span></div>
    </div>
 
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      This project started as a class assignment and grew into a full engineering challenge.
      I wanted to understand how feedback control systems work in practice, so I decided to design
      and fabricate every component myself rather than use a kit.
    </p>
 
    <h2>The Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Getting a robot to follow a line sounds simple — until the track curves sharply or the lighting
      changes. Basic bang-bang control creates jittery, oscillating motion. I needed a smoother solution.
    </p>
 
    <h2>My Approach</h2>
    <p>
      I implemented a PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) controller to smooth out corrections.
      The sensors read the line position and the controller adjusts each motor's speed independently
      to minimize error. I tuned the Kp, Ki, and Kd constants iteratively over a week of track testing.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>5-channel IR sensor array for precise position detection</li>
      <li>Two DC motors with PWM speed control via L298N H-bridge</li>
      <li>Custom chassis laser-cut from 3mm acrylic</li>
      <li>Arduino Uno as the main controller</li>
    </ul>
 
    <div class="img-grid">
      <div class="img-placeholder">📸 Chassis photo</div>
      <div class="img-placeholder">📸 Circuit layout</div>
    </div>
 
    <h2>Outcome</h2>
    <p>
      After tuning, the robot completed a complex track with sharp S-curves in 12.4 seconds with
      less than 2% lateral deviation. I presented this at my school's engineering showcase and was
      invited to demonstrate it at the district STEM fair.
    </p>
 
    <h2>What I Learned</h2>
    <p>
      PID tuning requires patience and a systematic approach — I learned to change one variable at a time
      and document results. I also got much more comfortable reading datasheets and debugging hardware
      issues with a multimeter and oscilloscope.
    </p>
 
